honestly it was good training for adult life in that you rapidly learn that people have all kinds of shit going on with them and it's almost never any of your business and you need not look or comment

for instance, we did not eat in the cafeteria. it was simply too small. instead we were free to eat anywhere in the building or go off campus if we could drive/had rides. all the kids who cared about grades met in one particular spot and we all did everything together basically.

yeah i think a major saving grace for me was that my high school had about ~4,000 kids in it. it was bigger than my university. it functioned like a small town. you knew people in your small group of friends/associates, but never even interacted w other groups of kids https://t.co/70KMvhDWce

...but what a strange and sudden transformation. millennial joke culture developed in the context of huge destabilizing events, and in some sense is a way of putting emotional distance between oneself and those events. but i guess this is the limit of that whole mien.

i have a sense of humor about bad things happening to me personally, and a set of principles with respect to what i take to be trolling which result in my having a very strong aversion to showing signs of being seriously upset, like for real emotional, on the internet...

i've never felt more radically torn between 2 versions of myself -- millennial left irony poster with brain poisoning from growing up online, and person who would earnestly support virtually any policy to avoid exposing her children to significant risk of living thru nuclear war https://t.co/gcmTccAQyy
